Scientists recently sent a probe into the ice of Taylor Glacier to extract salty samples of water from the main vein that feeds the red-stained feature.

'This is going to be an exciting sample to play with,' Jill Mikucki, an assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Tennessee told The Antarctic Sun.

She explained that Blood Falls' deep red hue is caused by the discharge of iron-rich, brine liquid.

Its chemistry is changed by bacteria, which transforms sulphur and iron compounds in order to survive.

