'It can drive curved trajectories through bulk ice. It can go sideways, up and down. If you want to reach any point, you can go there,' Dirk Heinen, a German physicist told The Antarctic Sun.

To help the probe navigate, scientists sent acoustic pulses from the surface into the ice.

This is similar to a GPS but uses different kinds of waves that use sound to track the position of the IceMole.

